{"type":"message","id":"65a9855c","parentId":"8f563c39","timestamp":"2026-04-23T21:00:41.002Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Today is Thursday, April 23rd, 2026. Tomorrow is Friday, April 24th, 2026. Friday's topic is \"Java OOP + Collections\". Category should be \"ctdl\" or maybe \"backend-dev\"? Given the topics listed, \"Java OOP + Collections\" seems more like a general programming topic. Let me check the categories available.\n\nThe user says:\n- Mon → CTDL: Arrays & Sorting\n- Tue → CTDL: Tree & Graph\n- Wed → C++ Thực chiến\n- Thu → JavaScript Patterns\n- Fri → Java OOP + Collections\n\n\n- Sat → DSA: Dynamic Programming\n- Sun → Python cho người mới\n\nFor categories, I'm mapping them to either 'ctdl' or 'web-dev'. Java OOP + Collections fits better with 'web-dev' since it's backend-focused, and DSA topics like Arrays & Sorting, Tree & Graph, and Dynamic Programming all map to 'ctdl'. I'm noticing some inconsistencies in the category assignments though—JavaScript Patterns is marked as 'web-dev' despite being a pattern guide, while C++ Thực chiến is 'ctdl' even though it's more of a practical guide.\n\nLet me just go with the straightforward mapping: Java OOP + Collections becomes 'web-dev' since it's a backend language topic, then I'll set up the article parameters with the date April 24th, 2026, the title \"Java OOP + Collections: Từ Cơ Bản Đến Chuyên Sâu\", content around 500-800 words with code examples, the web-dev category, and tags like 'java', 'oop', 'collections', 'tutorial', and 'backend-dev'.\n\nNow I'm thinking about the scheduling—tomorrow at 19:00 ICT, which is UTC+7, so that's 12:00 UTC on April 24th, 2026. I should check what directory structure exists in the content folder first before spawning the article-writing agent.","thinkingSignature":"4ef790b7bb704627f994807c65fb25a4fbd6c0f9f00851c17da82128db0c9f1c"},{"type":"text","text":"Today is Thursday → tomorrow is Friday → topic: **Java OOP + Collectio